This report presents a summary of findings for a Traffic Impact Analysis (TIA)
performed by Bury+Partners (Bury) for the proposed South Lamar Mixed Use
development located at the near the 3200 Block of South Lamar Boulevard in Austin,
Travis County, Texas. A site location map has been included in the Appendix of this
report as Exhibit 1. The purpose of this report is to document the change in existing
traffic volumes generated by the existing development and understand the impact of the
redevelopment of the site on the roadway network. The existing Auto Parts and
Service Center, New Car Retailer, and Health/Fitness Club are planned to be
redeveloped; the Broken Spoke dance hall, however will remain unchanged.
South Lamar Boulevard Mixed Use development is planned to be a mixed use
development that will be fully built-out by 2014. The various land-uses proposed are
Apartments, Specialty Retail, Coffee Shop, and High Turnover (Sit Down) Restaurant.
The associated sizes for the land-uses can be seen within Table 1. Access to the site will
be restricted to three (3) driveways with the southernmost driveway being the primary
means of access for 260 (of 360) of the Apartment dwelling units, the High Turnover
(Sit-Down) Restaurant, and the Coffee Shop. The conceptual site plan for the proposed
development has been included within the Appendix of this report as Exhibit 2.
Currently, the site contains an existing Auto Parts and Service Center, New Car Retailer,
and Health/Fitness Club; these land uses will be completely removed and replaced by the
Based on recommendations and data contained in the Institute of Transportation
Engineers Trip Generation manual, the proposed project will generate a net addition of
approximately 5,619 unadjusted daily trips upon full build-out in 2014. Table 1 provides
a detailed summary of traffic production for each land-use, which is directly related to
the assumed land-use plan. The trip generation outputs and associated rates have been
included as Exhibit 3 within the Appendix of this report.

This study consists of five (5) major components listed below.
Data Collection and Roadway System – Peak hour manual turning movement
counts (TMC) were performed from 7:00 a.m. to 9:00 a.m. and 4:00 p.m. to
6:00 p.m. in January 2012. In addition, Average Daily Traffic (ADT) counting
tubes were placed at two (2) locations within the study area for a 24-hour period in
January 2012. All TMC and ADT data is included within the Appendix of this
Trip Generation – An estimation of new trips generated by the proposed
development was determined using the Institute of Transportation Engineers Trip
Generation Handbook, 8th Edition as well as research done by Bury;
Trip Distribution – The origins and destinations of site-related trips were
determined by comparing existing traffic patterns on the study area roadways and
by observing the existing land use in the area;
Trip Assignment – New trips were assigned to the completion of the development
Analysis – An operational analysis of the surrounding roadway network was
completed for the 2012 Existing traffic and 2014 Forecasted and
2014 Site+Forecasted conditions. The existing and projected traffic volume
figures are within the Appendix of this report as Exhibit 6.

Pass-by and internal trips can account for a significant portion of a site’s generated
traffic. Internal trips use only internal roadways within the site traveling from one land
use to another. Pass-by trips are attracted to the site from traffic passing on an adjacent
street and are based on information contained in the ITE Trip Generation Handbook
(Trip Generation Handbook, ITE). Based on the scope provided by the City of Austin,
no internal trips or transit trips were accounted for in this analysis.
Assuming full build out; South Lamar Boulevard Mixed Use redevelopment is estimated
to generate a net addition of 630 trips in the AM peak hour (263 entering, 367 exiting)
and a net addition of 380 trips in the PM peak hour (229 entering, 191 exiting) which are
adjusted trips. The total adjusted 24-hour generated trips are 5,007 vehicles. Table 5
contains results of internal capture and pass-by adjustments to the traffic volumes.

The distribution of site traffic was based upon the turning movement counts and tube
counts collected at the study intersections. These data provided the basis for the
directional distribution of traffic approaching and departing the project site, which is
summarized in Table 6. The traffic distribution map can also be seen visually in the
Appendix of this report as Exhibit 8.
New site generated trips were assigned to the roadway network in accordance with the
trip distribution patterns determined earlier in this study. Trips to and from the site were
assigned to each study area roadway and each study area intersection. The existing 2012
traffic volumes were increased using a conservative growth factor determine from data
obtained from historic (2005 through 2010) TxDOT average annual daily trips. The
growth rate utilized for the roadway network within the analysis is two (2) percent.
All traffic generated by South Lamar Boulevard Mixed Use redevelopment was
distributed throughout the study area and added to the forecasted condition AM and PM
Peak Hour volumes which are shown in Exhibit 6. Trip assignment to the proposed site
driveways was based on the proposed locations of the land uses identified. As previously
discussed, access to the site will be limited to three (3) driveways with the southernmost
driveway (Driveway A) being the principal means of access for 260 (of 360) of the
Apartment dwelling units, the High Turnover (Sit-Down) Restaurant, and the Coffee
Shop. The remaining land uses, the Specialty Retail and 100 Apartment dwelling units,
in addition to the Broken Spoke will access the sites primarily by Driveways B and C.
Following the assignment of projected traffic volumes onto the study area roadways, a
detailed operational analysis was undertaken using techniques outlined in the
Highway Capacity Manual 2000 (HCM 2000). For purposes of traffic operational analyses,
geometric conditions within the study area were input into the microcomputer based traffic
model, Synchro, Version 7.0 (Husch, Snychro 7.0). A detailed operational analysis was
undertaken to evaluate each intersection’s peak hour capacity and LOS. Synchro follows
procedures developed in the HCM 2000 and analyzes the study area in its entirety, rather than
as a series of isolated intersections and driveways. All of the various scenarios, including
existing and proposed conditions for this study area were analyzed using Synchro.
For the evaluation of existing and proposed conditions, measurements of effectiveness (MOE)
were utilized such as intersection delay and LOS associated with this delay. The intersection
delay is the average control delay for the signalized intersection and is calculated by taking a
volumes-weighted average of all the delays occurring at the intersection. LOS refers to the
operational conditions within a traffic stream and their perception by motorists in terms of
delay, freedom to maneuver, traffic interruptions, comfort, convenience, and safety. There
are six (6) LOS capacity conditions for each roadway facility. These are designated from
"A" to "F," with "A" representing a free-flow optimal condition and "F" representing a
congested forced flow condition. The general criteria associated with each LOS reported for
